# Agentic SDLC Scaffolding

A baseline directory structure for multi-agent software development workflows using Cursor.
Based on Cursor's official [agent best practices](https://cursor.com/blog/agent-best-practices) and
[customizing agents](https://cursor.com/learn/customizing-agents) documentation.

---

## Directory Structure

```
.
├── AGENTS.md                          # Universal agent instructions (all tools)
├── README.md                          # This file
│
├── .cursor/
│   ├── rules/                         # Persistent, scoped agent rules
│   │   ├── 00-project-conventions.mdc
│   │   ├── 01-code-style.mdc
│   │   ├── 02-testing.mdc
│   │   ├── 03-git-workflow.mdc
│   │   └── 04-guardrails.mdc
│   │
│   ├── plans/                         # Saved implementation plans
│   │   └── TEMPLATE.md
│   │
│   ├── commands/                      # Reusable slash-command workflows
│   │   ├── pr.md
│   │   ├── review.md
│   │   ├── fix-issue.md
│   │   └── update-deps.md
│   │
│   ├── skills/                        # Dynamic, on-demand agent capabilities
│   │   ├── deploy-staging/SKILL.md
│   │   ├── code-review/SKILL.md
│   │   ├── test-loop/SKILL.md
│   │   └── onboard/SKILL.md
│   │
│   ├── memory/
│   │   └── active-context.md          # Agent working memory (current task + progress)
│   └── mcp.json                       # MCP server configuration (Context7)
│
└── docs/
    ├── architecture/                  # System architecture documentation
    │   └── TEMPLATE.md
    └── adr/                           # Architecture Decision Records
        └── TEMPLATE.md
```

---

## Directory Purposes

### `AGENTS.md` — Universal Agent Instructions

The single source of truth for all AI agents working in this repository, regardless of tool
(Cursor, Claude, Codex, etc.). Defines the project overview, essential commands, repository
conventions, agent boundaries (what agents may and must not do), and the verification
checklist every agent must satisfy before raising a PR.

> **When to edit**: project setup, onboarding a new tool, changing deployment conventions,
> or adding/removing protected paths.

---

### `.cursor/rules/` — Persistent Agent Rules

Markdown (`.mdc`) files loaded by Cursor at the start of every conversation.
Rules with `alwaysApply: true` are always injected; rules with `globs` apply only
when matching files are open. Think of these as the team's always-on coding standards.

| File | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `00-project-conventions.mdc` | Build commands, directory layout, post-change checklist |
| `01-code-style.mdc` | Naming, imports, error handling, canonical examples |
| `02-testing.mdc` | Test framework, TDD workflow, coverage expectations |
| `03-git-workflow.mdc` | Branching strategy, commit format, PR rules |
| `04-guardrails.mdc` | Protected paths, security rules, scope discipline |

> **Best practice**: Keep each rule under 50 lines, scoped to one concern.
> Add a rule only when you notice an agent making the same mistake repeatedly.
> Check all rules into git so the whole team benefits.

---

### `.cursor/plans/` — Approved Implementation Plans

Plans generated by Cursor's **Plan Mode** (`Shift+Tab` in agent input).
Before any non-trivial implementation, the agent researches the codebase, asks clarifying
questions, and produces a plan — then **waits for explicit approval** before saving or
implementing anything.

The approval gate works as follows:

1. Agent produces the plan and presents it for review.
2. Reviewer (human or orchestrating agent) approves, requests changes, or rejects it.
3. Only after explicit approval does the agent write the plan to `.cursor/plans/` and begin implementation.

> **This folder is a record of approved work, not a drafts folder.**
> A file here means the plan was reviewed and committed to. Unapproved drafts are never saved.
>
> **Naming convention**: `YYYY-MM-DD-<slug>.md`
>
> **Why it matters**: Plans create a reviewable audit trail, allow interrupted work to be
> resumed by any agent, and prevent scope creep by stating explicitly which files will
> and will not be changed.

---

### `.cursor/commands/` — Reusable Slash-Command Workflows

Plain markdown files (no frontmatter) that define multi-step workflows.
You trigger them explicitly by typing `/name` in the agent input.
Use commands for operations where *you* always decide when to run them.

| Command | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `/pr` | Commit, push, and open a pull request |
| `/review` | Run quality checks and produce a structured review report |
| `/fix-issue [number]` | Fetch a GitHub issue, plan, fix, and open a PR |
| `/update-deps` | Update dependencies one at a time with verification after each |

> **Best practice**: Add a command only after you have manually performed a workflow
> several times and want to standardize it. Check commands into git for team reuse.

---

### `.cursor/skills/` — Auto-Discovered Agent Capabilities

Skills are a superset of commands. A skill is a `SKILL.md` file with a `description`
frontmatter that tells the agent *when* to load it. This means skills can be triggered
in two ways:

1. **Automatically** — the agent reads the `description` and loads the skill when it
   judges it relevant to your request (without you typing anything).
2. **Explicitly** — you can still invoke any skill manually with `/skill-name`, exactly
   like a command.

The `description` frontmatter is the only structural difference from a command file.
It unlocks auto-discovery and keeps the context window clean — a skill only consumes
context when actually relevant.

| Skill | Auto-triggers when… |
|---|---|
| `deploy-staging` | You ask to deploy, ship, or push to staging |
| `code-review` | You ask to review code, find bugs, or audit a PR |
| `test-loop` | You ask to iterate until tests pass or fix failing tests |
| `onboard` | You want a codebase tour or ask how the project works |

> **Commands vs Skills**: Use a command when you will always invoke it explicitly by name.
> Use a skill when the agent should also be able to discover and apply it on its own.
> Any command can be promoted to a skill by adding a `description` frontmatter.

---

### `.cursor/mcp.json` — MCP Server Configuration

Connects agents to external tools via the [Model Context Protocol](https://cursor.com/docs/context/model-context-protocol).
The baseline ships with **Context7** pre-configured — a free, no-account-required MCP server
that fetches current, version-accurate library documentation on demand.

Use it in any prompt:
```
use context7 for Next.js 15 app router conventions
use context7 with /prisma/prisma for relation query syntax
```

This prevents agents from generating code against stale API knowledge from training data.
An optional API key can be added to the `headers` field for higher rate limits.

> **Scope**: `.cursor/mcp.json` applies to this project only. To make Context7 (or any
> MCP server) available across all projects, add it to `~/.cursor/mcp.json` instead.

---

### `.cursor/memory/active-context.md` — Agent Working Memory

Persistent memory that bridges agent sessions. Because Cursor agents start each
conversation fresh with no built-in memory, this file provides continuity — the agent
reads it at session start to know what is in progress, and updates it before ending
so the next session can resume exactly where things stopped.

The file is intentionally minimal — one active task at a time:

| Field | Purpose |
|---|---|
| **Current Task** | Task title, branch, plan reference, and status |
| **Progress** | Checklist of steps — checked as completed |
| **Stopped At** | Last action done + exact next action to resume |

When a task is fully complete the file is cleared entirely. An empty file means
no task is in progress. This keeps the file small and the context cost low.

Agents are instructed in `AGENTS.md` to read this file at session start and update
it before ending every session.

---

### `docs/architecture/` — System Architecture Documentation

Markdown files describing the architecture of significant systems or features, using
Mermaid diagrams for context maps and sequence flows. Written by agents or humans
and reviewed as part of the PR process for any non-trivial change.

> **When to add**: Any change that introduces a new service, changes a data flow,
> or makes an architectural trade-off worth documenting.

---

### `docs/adr/` — Architecture Decision Records

Lightweight records of important architectural decisions — the context, the options
considered, and the rationale for the chosen approach. ADRs are immutable once
accepted; superseded decisions get a new ADR rather than an edit.

> **Naming convention**: `ADR-NNN-<slug>.md`
>
> **Why it matters**: ADRs give agents (and future team members) the "why" behind
> design choices, preventing well-intentioned refactors that unknowingly reverse
> deliberate decisions.

---

## Contributing

This section applies to both human contributors and AI agents working in this repository.

### Starting a Task

1. **Understand the scope** — read the relevant issue or ticket before touching any code.
2. **Plan before coding** — for anything non-trivial, use Plan Mode (`Shift+Tab` in the
   agent input). The agent will research the codebase, ask clarifying questions, and
   produce a plan for your review.
3. **Approve the plan** — review it, request changes if needed, and give explicit approval.
   The agent saves it to `.cursor/plans/YYYY-MM-DD-<slug>.md` only after approval and
   begins implementation immediately after. Plans are never saved before approval.
4. **Create a branch** — branch off `develop` using the naming convention in
   `.cursor/rules/03-git-workflow.mdc` (`feat/<slug>`, `fix/<slug>`, `chore/<slug>`).

### Implementing

- Follow the conventions in `.cursor/rules/` — they are the authoritative style guide.
- Use Context7 (`use context7`) when writing code against external libraries to ensure
  you are working with current API documentation.
- Make only changes relevant to the stated task — see `.cursor/rules/04-guardrails.mdc`
  for protected paths and scope discipline.
- Keep commits atomic and use Conventional Commits format.

### Before Opening a PR

Run the full verification loop and confirm every item passes:

- [ ] Typecheck — zero errors
- [ ] Tests — all pass, new behavior has coverage
- [ ] Lint — zero warnings
- [ ] No secrets or credentials in the diff
- [ ] No protected paths modified without explicit approval
- [ ] No unrelated files changed

The complete checklist lives in `AGENTS.md`. Use the `/review` command to run it
automatically.

### Opening a PR

Run `/pr` — it will commit, push, and open a pull request with a structured description.
Target branch is `develop` (not `main`). PRs require at least one human approval before
merging; agents do not self-merge.

### Updating Conventions

If you notice the agent making the same mistake repeatedly, update the relevant rule
file in `.cursor/rules/` as part of the same PR. If you introduce a new specialized
workflow, add it as a skill in `.cursor/skills/` or a command in `.cursor/commands/`.
Commit all of these to git so the whole team benefits immediately.

---

## Quick-Start Checklist

After cloning this scaffold into your project:

- [ ] Fill in the project overview and commands in `AGENTS.md`
- [ ] Update build/test/lint commands in `.cursor/rules/00-project-conventions.mdc`
- [ ] Add canonical file examples to `.cursor/rules/01-code-style.mdc`
- [ ] Configure your test runner in `.cursor/rules/02-testing.mdc`
- [ ] Update protected paths in `.cursor/rules/04-guardrails.mdc`
- [ ] Replace `<deploy-staging-command>` in `.cursor/skills/deploy-staging/SKILL.md`
- [ ] Commit everything to git so your whole team benefits

